metadata.name: Mythologic #881
metadata.description:
"Mythologic" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

Mythologic is a project derived from cloud series, Cloud Atlas and Requiem: Cloud on fxhash. In the series, lines and circles are used in an organics movement like Cloud Hands, which is a move of Tai Chi. Practitioners move their hands slowly and smoothly, make circles and rotate with extreme concentrating. In Chinese we said “floating clouds and flowing water” to describe calligraphers’ freely flowing style of writing. Chi is a very important for oriental artists, and for genart as well. In the series, lines and circles start from one position to another, and develop with organic rotations and movements, like practicing Tai Chi on the canvas. 

Mythologic was inspired from “Classic of Mountains and Seas”, also known as Shan Hai Jing, is a Chinese classic text and a compilation of mythic geography and beasts. 

“There is a beast that looks like a fox with nine tails.” 
“Huangbei: it is a beetle with meat like a tadpole, but with a head and a tail” 
“The beast has the body of a fish but the wings of a bird” 

There are many incredible creatures in the text which describe the oriental fantasy. The idea of Mythologic is to present an illustrated handbook with random generated paintings, each one is like a framed badge, to memorize the glorious age. It uses the "cloud hands" technique in every parts of this piece, the center, the circle and the frame. They are all the same algorithm but perform variety with different density and components. Gold, Silver, Copper, Jade and Ruby colors as noble symbol of treasure in Chinese culture. 

This project use p5js. 

Press 'S' to save pictures.

Thanks to the support of Yi-Wen Lin in this project.

metadata.name: The Wintertime #10
metadata.description:
"The Wintertime" is a collection of generative art that captures the essence of the winter season in a glitchy and abstract way. The pieces in this collection are a visual representation of the harshness and beauty of winter, where the cold and barren landscapes are juxtaposed against the sparkling snow and ice. The glitches and digital distortions in the art add a sense of chaos and unpredictability, mirroring the unpredictable nature of winter weather. The collection celebrates the winter season in all its raw and untamed glory. Each piece is unique and evocative, inviting the viewer to get lost in the beauty of the wintertime.

The work was inspired by the drip painting technique of Jackson Pollock and the minimalistic elegance of Japanese prints. Combining these two distinct styles creates a visually striking and thought-provoking collection that pays homage to the masters while pushing the boundaries of contemporary art.

This collection is the continuation of GPTree: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/17691

Genuary 2023: Recursive trees

metadata.name: Gkrint #44
metadata.description:
Gkrint is a celebration of minimalism, colour, and space using the humble grid, a foundation of generative art, and movement. Through this collaboration, Ballzerino and George explore the relationships between these elements.

Inspired by the timeless principles of Bauhaus design, Ballzerino carefully curated custom colour palettes and selected geometric shapes, while George encoded the creative process into an algorithm, bringing the compositions to life, and putting the CPU to work finding new and unexpected compositions within our framework.

Gkrint is Ballzerino's genesis generative art drop.

Controls:
SPACE - pause / resume
click (or tap) - change colour selection (within same palette)
hold 'f' - speed up animation

Tested on Windows / Mac / iOS / Android. Chrome recommended for the best experience.

metadata.name: Circumscript #42
metadata.description:
It has always been a goal of mine to incorporate the worlds of physical and digital art together in a piece. And with circumscript I am the closest I've ever been. Circumscript uses a custom shader written to mix and "dilute" the colors on the canvas, thus creating a very physical feeling piece.

This dilution can be more or less depending on the edition, but always plays a huge role in the feel of the piece.


Happy new year.


----


[m] or [double tap] : opens the export/settings menu, use this menu to change the resolution, and make sure to press the reload button if you do.
[holding down] : zooms in on a certain area of the piece, depending on where your mouse/finger is. Use this feature to expore the complex textures of the piece in more detail, it's highly recommended to do this on a higher resolution setting.

The outputs can vary slighty per device, as there's a slight difference in how certain math gets interpreted on different devices with shaders.


----


Made with p5.js and webgl by Wouter Missler in 2022/3.

metadata.name: Bellissimas #5
metadata.description:
Expressive portraits inspired by @michelepetrelli 

The used techniques search in the unexplored field of mixing pfp layer based work and real-time generative algorithms changing and adding to the premade assets.

The pre-generated assets include original artworks by Petrelli, Imitations of Petrelli's work by @brutalisti, GAN generated artworks inspired by Petrelli using several different AI technologies.

Every generatively chosen layer combination is live-processed and generatively altered in aspects of color and shape. Then the generative algorithm proceed with captured color palettes and generate background and additional drawing over and under the initial layers. The final result as acquired by visualizing everything with live generative algorithm that give additional layer of uniqueness.

Project by  @michelepetrelli & @brutalisti, curated by XCOLLABS

metadata.name: Versus in Motion #127
metadata.description:
"Versus in Motion" is an animated version, a successor of original "Versus" collection
https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/21865

Includes all features of "Versus" (resolution levels, switchable orientation, etc) plus it's animated (obviously) and interactive
- You can stop & start animation at any time by pressing the spacebar
- You may click (or click & drag) while in animation or not, to modify the current artwork

Animation cycle is actually a transition between a "full" and an "empty" state that symbolizes the transition between existence, non-existence,  prosperity & decline and the evolution and progress in general as a result of time passage..

All are pure code, shapes and curves that processed in a custom fragment glsl (webgl) shader using a relative "advanced" developed mixing technique.

CONTROLS

KEYS:

- 1-4: Set resolution from 1x to 4x of the current dimension (possibly slower performance in higher values)
- S: Save a png file with the current resolution

- P: Change orientation to Portrait with aspect ratio 0.75 (useful eg. for printing)
- L: Change orientation to Landscape with ratio 4/3  (1.333..)
- O: Original orientation. That is the default Square (box)
  Due to some 1:1 ratio sensitive calculations, rendering output may differ when switching 
  orientations

  For animation:
- Spacebar: toggle animation (on/off)
- R: Reset the center of animation (if has been modified with click or drag)

MOUSE:

- Click (or Click & Drag) to set the center of animation

----
Made with p5js and custom shaders

© Dec. 2022  @Uniray_net | uniray.net

metadata.name: Hex-a-Sketch #86
metadata.description:
Truchet tiling with hexagons, drawn with three amounts of sketchiness in p5.js.  I had a lot of fun with this!  I love how it often looks like pastels, and sometimes like crayons.  Sometimes it reminds me of basket weaves or a quilt, or a warm sweater.  The super-sketchy can look chaotic, like it's trying to jump off the page, but if it weren't being made sketchy, then all the tiling would sync together in one form.  The foreground says, "look at me!" But then you notice the background with its nuance and depth.  It's like a dance between the two - the yin and the yang.  

I love sharing what I’ve learned about gen art and inspiring others on my YouTube channel, Steve’s Makerspace.

After clicking open:
press 2 - 5 to increase pixel density
press s to save a png

Resize goes back to pixel density 1.
